{
  category: "Electricity Network",
  definitions: [
    {
      term: "Distributed Energy Resources",
      acronyms: [ "DER" ],
      synonyms: [ "Distributed Energy", "Decentralised Energy", "Distributed Generation", "Embedded Generation" ],
      usedVeryFrequently: true,
      definition: {
        summary:
        "Physical electricity hardware that provides energy production, consumption, or storage at a low magnitude \
         compared to traditional grid-scale technology like large power plants. \
         The resources are \"distributed\" because they exist across a wide area within a network, in contrast to larger \
         resources which are in a small number of locations.",
        more:
        "The category of DER contains a wide variety and scale of devices. \
        At the lower end of the DER spectrum are [Consumer Energy Resources] (CER). \
        DER also includes non-consumer-scale technologies that have high cardinality and are geographically distributed, \
        such as small-scale [Commercial & Industrial] solar or wind farms, [Community Batteries], \
        small hydropower stations or small [Pumped Hydro]. \
        (In some contexts, DER may mean just CER, not larger distributed resources.)"
      },
      links: [
        { title: "Wikipedia", href: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distributed_generation" },
        { title: "IEA", href: "https://www.iea.org/reports/unlocking-the-potential-of-distributed-energy-resources/executive-summary" },
        { title: "Infographic", href: "https://www.aemc.gov.au/sites/default/files/content//ERC0191-AEMC-Embedded-Generation-Infographic_FINAL.PDF" },
        { title: "YouTube", href: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TlecJcCJ7zg" },
      ],
    },
    {
      term: "Virtual Power Plant",
      acronyms: [ "VPP" ],
      usedVeryFrequently: true,
      definition: {
        summary:
        "A group of [Distributed Energy Resources] that can be controlled collectively and remotely to increase or \
        decrease electricity supply or demand in a network, or to provide other [ancillary services].",
        more:
        "The \"power plant\" designation recognises that, together, the grouped resources can have a high-magnitude \
        effect on a network equivalent to a traditional grid-scale plant, while the \"virtual\" moniker recognises \
        that the \"plant\" does not exist in a physical form, but only by virtue of their being controlled as a group.",
      },
      links: [
        { title: "ARENA", href: "https://arena.gov.au/blog/what-are-virtual-power-plants-and-why-do-they-matter/" },
        { title: "Wikipedia", href: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_power_plant" },
